# Commits

- **English**, brief and precise — state exactly what changed.
- One logical change per commit; focused diffs only.
- Use imperative mood: `Add Product migration`, not `Added` or `Adding`.
- Subject line ≤ 72 characters; no trailing period.
- Body optional — only when context is not obvious from the subject.

```
# Good
Add Catalog Product and Category migrations
Register ProductCatalogInterface in CatalogServiceProvider
Fix stock decrement rollback on order failure

# Bad
fix stuff
WIP
updates
Refactored some things and also fixed tests and updated readme
```

- Clear commit history required for submission (per assignment).

# Code Quality

- Run **Laravel Duster** before committing; all style checks must pass.
- **Larastan** level ≥ 5 with zero errors — set up in Phase 0, not deferred.
- **GitHub Actions** CI from Phase 0: Pest + Duster + Larastan.
- All **Pest** feature tests must pass before submission (see `testing.mdc`).
- Minimize scope — focused diffs, no unrelated changes.
- Match existing conventions; reuse abstractions over reimplementing.
- Type hints and clear Laravel patterns.

# Code Ownership

- Understand every architectural decision — live review will require explaining and modifying code in real time.
- AI tools are allowed; validate against current official docs (Laravel, Filament, Livewire, nwidart).
- Do not submit code you cannot explain or defend.

# Submission

- Public GitHub repo, tag `v1.0`.
- `.cursor/rules/` committed to the repo.
- Build from scratch in this repository.
- Migrations for all entities; seeded demo data.
- Application runs without errors before submission.
- Verify README instructions on a fresh environment.

## README (required before v1.0)

- Installation steps, database setup, environment configuration, asset compilation
- How to start the app (Sail), access admin, test main functionality
- Test commands: all tests + module-specific tests + any test setup
- Architecture overview: module structure, cross-module communication, patterns used
- Demo instructions for evaluators

# Principles

- Clean architecture over complex features.
- Official documentation drives decisions — understand the "why" behind patterns.
- Document architectural thought process in README.
